post_text: Tonight our board made a courageous vote to stick with our reopening plan. With careful consideration of the governor’s recommendation and the feedback received from our local community they have chosen to proceed with our “parent choice model” of choosing between in person instruction and the virtual academy to begin August 26. We appreciate the support of our community and the safety and well being of our students is always a top priority!
text: Tonight our board made a courageous vote to stick with our reopening plan. With careful consideration of the governor’s recommendation and the feedback received from our local community they have chosen to proceed with our “parent choice model” of choosing between in person instruction and the virtual academy to begin August 26. We appreciate the support of our community and the safety and well being of our students is always a top priority!

Good afternoon Williamstown family. The online registration window has been open this week for students in Kindergarten through 12th grade and will remain open until noon on Friday, August 7. If you have not been contacted by a staff member to complete your child's registration you will have until this time to do so. The district has many plans to finalize including preparing the facility, instructional delivery methods, professional learning, etc. and the number of students returning to school will play a major factor in these plans. Therefore, those students whose registration has not been submitted by noon Friday will be placed in the Williamstown Virtual Learning Academy for the first semester of the school year. If you have issues with the registration process please contact the school office for assistance. Thank you for your attention, flexibility and understanding as we work to meet the needs of our school community.

Thanks.
Todd Dupin
Director of Pupil Personnel

All registrations must be completed by a parent/guardian in the household through the online process and will only take a few minutes to update your information. Registration is needed on or before August 5 so further plans can be made at each school.

Please view registration/enrollment information on the district website for specific details. If you have questions regarding the registration process please contact your child's school office and ask to speak with the registrar. Remember, all returning families will use your Infinite Campus Parent Portal account to complete registration.

post_text:
Dear Families,
Many of you have probably heard the KHSAA has lifted their dead period effective today. It is always our goal to ensure safety of our students and this includes our student athletes. The Board of Education and school and district administration will be meeting to discuss the KHSAA and Governor guidelines for a safe reopening to athletic and non-athletic activities. The first phase is June 1-June 14 and is considered a “communication phase”. There will be no face-to-face athletic or non-athletic activities held on or off campus, but coaches can meet virtually with their team or players. June 15-June 29 is Phase 2 and will allow some conditioning and skill work. Once again, we will work with the BOE, coaches and administrators to develop a plan for this phase. Once this plan is developed we will communicate with all stakeholders. Please be aware that this plan will be fluid as we continue to receive information on the ever changing guidelines and circumstances surrounding COVID-19.

Thank you!

GRADUATION DAY HAS ARRIVED! First, parents of seniors have put together a parade beginning at 5:00 this evening. While this is not sponsored by school we want to remind and encourage participants to practice the safety guidelines and stay socially distant. The parade will begin at the old courthouse and travel north to Tractor Supply where they will cross the bridge and then head back to school for a tassel turn and cap throwing. Please line the route and show your support for these students. When you arrive on our campus you MUST stay 6 feet apart from those not in your immediate family. Please follow these guidelines!

At 7:00 virtual graduation will begin. While we won’t be together in a gym we can take comfort knowing we are all watching it together remotely. You can watch via the following methods:

Williamstown Independent Schools Facebook Page
Williamstown Independent Schools Youtube Channel: https://bit.ly/WISD_Youtube.
Williamstown Cable Channel 16
Spectrum Cable Channel 186

Congratulations Class of 2020! We are proud of you!

post_text: Williamstown HS senior Cameron Mirones recently signed a national letter of intent with Georgetown College to continue his education and baseball career with the Tigers. Cameron, a right-handed pitcher, is the son of Tony and Pam Mirones and sibling of Alex and Zachary Mirones. During the 2019 season, Cameron earned selection to the 8th Region All “A” all-tournament team and finished with a 3-0 record in 29 innings for the Demons. We want to congratulate Cameron and his family on his signing and wish him well on the diamond at Georgetown!
text: Williamstown HS senior Cameron Mirones recently signed a national letter of intent with Georgetown College to continue his education and baseball career with the Tigers. Cameron, a right-handed pitcher, is the son of Tony and Pam Mirones and sibling of Alex and Zachary Mirones. During the 2019 season, Cameron earned selection to the 8th Region All “A” all-tournament team and finished with a 3-0 record in 29 innings for the Demons. We want to congratulate Cameron and his family on his signing and wish him well on the diamond at Georgetown!

post_text: Williamstown senior, Ben Kinsey, recently signed with Georgetown College to continue his running and academic career. Ben will participate in cross country and track for the Tigers. While running for the Demons, Ben was a member of a team that finished 4th at the 2019 Class A State championships, won the Class A Region title, and won the NCKC conference championship five times. We would like to congratulate Ben and his parents, Coach Mark and Julie Kinsey, and wish him well in his new adventure in Georgetown!

post_text: We hope you’ve had a great Easter and a restful break last week. This week we will be continuing with meal delivery, but each family requesting meals is asked to leave a box or some type of container by the driveway so we may drop the meals there and decrease contact and exposure. We appreciate your help in ensuring the safety of our staff so they can continue to serve you. As we begin another week of NTI, we encourage you to reach out to teachers or other staff for any guidance or help you need. While we aren’t physically together, we are still here to support our students and families, so please do not hesitate to reach out. Thank you for working with us through this difficult time. Together, we will get through this.

post_text:
Want to Learn More About Grade Level Expectations? Check out the Standards Family Guides!

The Kentucky Academic Standards (KAS) Family Guides were developed by the Kentucky Department of Education to help families familiarize themselves with the content of each grade level’s standards. Each grade level guide contains a standards overview for reading and writing, mathematics, science and social studies that includes suggestions for ways you can incorporate learning into your daily activities. Now more than ever, the Standards Family Guides are a great resource to help you meet your child’s learning needs.

Please contact me, your child's teacher or principal if you have any questions.
Amy Harris, Instructional Supervisor

https://kystandards.org/standards-family-guides/

This evening, Governor Andy Beshear, recommended an extended closure for all school districts. School was intended to be back in regular session on March 30, but the new date for return is April 20.

We will continue with NTI days #3-#7 next week as planned. Students have lessons and activities to complete and food service will be available each day. Superintendent Middleton will provide more detailed information to all families early next week regarding the extended closure.

We miss our students and look forward to the day we can gather again. In the meantime, please take care of yourselves and continue to follow the recommendations of social distancing and good hygiene.

Thank you!

post_text:
This evening, Governor Andy Beshear advised districts to cease in person classes effective Monday, March 16 for the period of two weeks.

While school buildings will be closed, we will follow the NTI model beginning Wednesday, March 18. March 16 and 17, schools will be closed utilizing our banked days and staff will be working on lessons and assignments. Therefore, students will not have any assignments on Monday and Tuesday of next week.

More specific and formal communication will be shared in the upcoming days in regards to lessons, food service and other school activities. You can also refer to the letter sent earlier for more information.

School IS in session tomorrow and students will be advised to take home necessary materials in order to complete assignments while schools are closed.

Therefore, students will not have any assignments on Monday and Tuesday of next week.

More specific and formal communication will be shared in the upcoming days in regards to lessons, food service and other school activities. You can also refer to the letter sent earlier for more information.

School IS in session tomorrow and students will be advised to take home necessary materials in order to complete assignments while schools are closed.

post_text:
Superintendent Middleton sent a letter to all families and staff with an update on COVID-19 through email this evening. The letter is also posted on the district website and social media accounts. School IS in session tomorrow.

While the Governor has asked school districts to be prepared, he has not yet directed schools to close. If and when, a closure announcement is made, district leadership will immediately notify families and staff of next steps for our district. The school district will follow the direction of the Governor and local health department to make these important decisions. As always, the safety of our students and staff are the number one priority.

Thank you!!

post_text:
The Williamstown Board of Education is accepting nominations for the 2020 Wall of Fame. This award was created by the Board of Education to recognize Williamstown High School graduates who have made a unique and special contribution to society through their work or other notable activities.

A committee will select the winning candidate from the nominations received. Nominations shall include:
Candidate's name and contact information
A narrative describing the basis for the nomination
Nominator's name and contact information
Deadline for submitting nominations is Monday, April 27, 2020 at 3:00 p.m. Send the nomination to:
Wall of Fame
c/o Williamstown Board of Education
300 Helton Street
Williamstown, KY 41097

or email nominations to misty.middleton@williamstown.kyschools.us

For questions please contact the District Office at 859-824-7144. The recipient will be recognized at the commencement exercises currently scheduled for May 22, 2020 at 7:00 p.m.

post_text: It’s official! Williamstown Middle School Archery has made it to state! The team will be competing on Friday March 13, where they will shoot against 7800 other NASP archers from across the state. Their flight time is set for 10:00 AM in the North Wing of the Expo Center in Louisville, KY. It’s the first time since 2016 that Williamstown has had a team qualify for state. We would love for anyone who can make the trip to come out and support the Williamstown Middle School Archery team.

post_text: Mrs. Kirk and Mrs. Drysdale collaborated to create a unit through a grant from the Northern Kentucky Cooperative for Educational Services. The unit had to integrate math and arts concepts. They chose to feature architectural elements, area and perimeter. Juniors and Seniors in Mr. Winkle's first period class filled out a client interest survey sheet.. Fourth graders were assigned one of these clients and built structures to meet client needs as well as area and perimeter constraints. Students used materials supplied by the grant and the Zero Landfill Foundation to create their projects. They were given cardboard, carpet, fabric, tile, and a variety of other art materials to create and build. Fourth graders revealed their structures to the high school students in a final celebration of their learning.

post_text:
Next week, October 21-25, we will be celebrating Red Ribbon and Safe Schools Week. Students are invited and encouraged to participate in the following dress up days. Prizes will be awarded by random drawing of those who participate!

Monday
Strong enough to show empathy for others who need help at school. “Super Silly Sock Day” -
Students wear their favorite socks.

Tuesday
Awesome, as I strive to use tolerance to create unity at school. “Athletic Day” -Choose your favorite team and wear their gear.

Wednesday
Friendly, showing kindness to others of all ages. “Funny Hat Day” – Students can wear their favorite funny hat.

Thursday
Encouraging, promoting a feeling of community and friendship throughout my school. “Extra Spirit Day” – Students wear school spirit t-shirts or school spirit wear.

Friday
“Rest Easy Day” -- Let’s all wear appropriate pajamas.

Afterwards he spoke to our sources of strength students to gain more information about how to spread the power of a promise around our school.

He has a powerful message and challenged us to apply the message in our everyday life. Ask your child about his message and take a look at their new wristband to serve as a reminder. Afterwards he spoke to our sources of strength students to gain more information about how to spread the power of a promise around our school.

post_text: We are excited to officially welcome David Fields as our new, and first ever, school resource officer! This is a great addition to make our campus even safer. His office is located in the high school hallway, but he will be all over campus once school begins. Welcome home Deputy Fields!
